The response trend of the fluorescence spectra of NCDs-AuNCs was evaluated with the addition of gradient concentrations of Pb2+. As illustrated in Fig. 4b, the fluorescence response at 460 nm gradually decayed with the increase of Pb2+ concentration, while the emission peak at 625 nm showed an obvious enhancement. A good linear relationship can be seen between the fluorescence intensity ratio (F625/F460) and Pb2+ concentration in the range of 0.86–20 μM (as indicated in Fig. 4c). The corresponding line regression equation can be formulated as F625/F460 = 0.027x + 0.648, where x represents the Pb2+ concentration (μm) and the correlation coefficient (R
                        2) was 0.991. The detection limit of Pb2+ was 0.68 μM calculated as the signal-to-noise ratio of 3. In comparison to other ratiometric fluorescence sensors for the detection of Pb2+ (Table 1
                        ), the synthesis method described in this study is simple, low-cost, and environmentally friendly, in which the hybridization of the two fluorescent materials does not require additional coupling agents. Moreover, the described analytical method showed good selectivity and anti-interference ability for the detection of Pb2+, indicating its extensive application scope.
